# Resolver Organization

Each GraphQL type has a "home" module under `src/<domain>/<type>.ts` that
exports `<type>Resolvers`. **All resolvers for a type's fields live in that
type's home module** — regardless of what type the field returns.

This includes back-pointer fields. A `Share.wishList` field resolver lives in
`share.ts` (Share's home), not in `wishlist.ts` — even though it resolves to a
`WishList`.

## Where things live

- `Foo.<field>` resolvers → `<foo>.ts`
- `Query.<field>` and `Mutation.<field>` resolvers → the home module of the
  type most central to that operation (e.g. `createShare` lives in `share.ts`)
- Each home module is wired into `src/schema.ts` via its `<type>Resolvers`
  export

## Example

```ts
// src/wishlist/share.ts — owns the Share type
export const shareResolvers = {
  Share: {
    wishList: async (parent, _, ctx) => { /* ... */ },
  },
  Mutation: {
    createShare: /* ... */,
  },
}

// src/wishlist/wishlist.ts — owns the WishList type
export const wishlistResolvers = {
  WishList: {
    shares: async (parent, _, ctx) => { /* ... */ },
    publicShare: async (parent, _, ctx) => { /* ... */ },
  },
}
```

## Why

Locating every resolver for a given type is a single-file lookup, and adding
a new type to the schema is a self-contained change: create the home module,
add its resolvers (including any back-pointers from related types), and
register it in `src/schema.ts`.
